<subSubSection id="6FA29EC4FFBAFF94FF5DF8B9FEDBF8DB" pageId="2" pageNumber="485" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2707CD4FFFBAFF94FF5DF8B9FEDBF8DB" blockId="2.[151,1437,1517,2012]" pageId="2" pageNumber="485">
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBAFF94FF5DF8B9FEF8F88C" bold="true" box="[199,334,1805,1831]" pageId="2" pageNumber="485">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is dedicated to Diego Matheus de Mello Mendes, a dear friend of the first author, in recognition of his significant contributions to the 
<taxonomicName id="E0B8B6CCFFBAFF94FD50F885FCF5F8E0" authorityName="Oliver" authorityYear="1789" box="[714,835,1841,1867]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="485" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Orthoptera</taxonomicName>
of 
<collectingCountry id="5FAF8DDFFFBAFF94FCF1F885FC04F8E0" box="[875,946,1841,1867]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="485">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, especially in the Amazon region of such a wonderful country.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6FA29EC4FFBAFF93FF5DF8CDFE44FF52" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="488" pageId="2" pageNumber="485" type="description">
<paragraph id="2707CD4FFFBAFF95FF5DF8CDFD10FD66" blockId="2.[151,1437,1517,2012]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,717]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="486" pageId="2" pageNumber="485">
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBAFF94FF5DF8CDFEEFF838" bold="true" box="[199,345,1913,1939]" pageId="2" pageNumber="485">Description.</emphasis>
In addition to the characters of the genus: 
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBAFF94FCA1F8CDFC2FF838" bold="true" box="[827,921,1913,1939]" pageId="2" pageNumber="485">Female.</emphasis>
Medium to large-sized compared to the other species of the genus (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBAFF94FE12F829FE7FF81C" box="[392,457,1949,1975]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,741,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-306@3.[151,1436,741,1883]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in dorsal and B. Lateral view, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413710/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="485">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Body predominantly dark brown, forelegs yellowish-brown, dactyls black with ocher base (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBAFF94FF41F875FEF4F870" box="[219,322,1985,2011]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,741,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-306@3.[151,1436,741,1883]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in dorsal and B. Lateral view, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413710/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="485">Figs. 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBAFF94FECAF875FEC0F870" box="[336,374,1985,2011]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-28@4.[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in frontal view. B. Head and inner side of fore leg. C. Outer side of fore leg. D. Tegmina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413712/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="485">2A</figureCitation>
), tympanum whitish (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBAFF94FDE9F875FD7BF870" box="[627,717,1985,2011]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-28@4.[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in frontal view. B. Head and inner side of fore leg. C. Outer side of fore leg. D. Tegmina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413712/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="485">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Mid-legs yellowish, hind legs with faded brown spots on an ocher background (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBBFF95FEF4FF23FE72FF1A" box="[366,452,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,741,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-306@3.[151,1436,741,1883]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in dorsal and B. Lateral view, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413710/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). Tegmina and hindwings yellowish-white, with yellowish-brown veins (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBBFF95FB6AFF23FAFCFF1A" box="[1264,1354,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-28@4.[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in frontal view. B. Head and inner side of fore leg. C. Outer side of fore leg. D. Tegmina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413712/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBBFF95FAC6FF23FA2AFF1A" bold="true" box="[1372,1436,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Head</emphasis>
slender with mouthparts ending in a conical shape when closed and covered by clipeus and labrum. Ovoid ocelli, medium size, greatest diameter 
<quantity id="E04060AAFFBBFF95FD9BFF6BFD1AFF52" box="[513,684,223,249]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" metricValueMax="2.1" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="486" unit="mm" value="0.205" valueMax="0.21" valueMin="0.2">0.20–0.21 mm</quantity>
.; interocellar distance 1.5 times the maximum width of one of the ocelli. Ocellar-ocular distance less than one ocellar length; interocular distance slightly greater than the length of compound eyes (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBBFF95FECDFE93FE07FEEA" box="[343,433,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-28@4.[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in frontal view. B. Head and inner side of fore leg. C. Outer side of fore leg. D. Tegmina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413712/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBBFF95FE5CFE93FD93FEEA" bold="true" box="[454,549,295,321]" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Thorax.</emphasis>
Pronotum elongated oval, almost twice as long as wide (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBBFF95FB30FE93FAB2FEEA" box="[1194,1284,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,741,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-306@3.[151,1436,741,1883]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in dorsal and B. Lateral view, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413710/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBBFF95FA83FE93FAEEFEEA" bold="true" box="[1305,1368,295,321]" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Legs.</emphasis>
Forefemur 1.8 times longer than wide. Process of fore femur almost as long as wide, apex rounded (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBBFF95FB54FEFFFAFAFECE" box="[1230,1356,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-28@4.[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in frontal view. B. Head and inner side of fore leg. C. Outer side of fore leg. D. Tegmina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413712/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Figs. 2B,C</figureCitation>
). Tympanum ovoid and elongated occupying 80% of the tibia base (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBBFF95FCC1FEDBFC03FE22" box="[859,949,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-28@4.[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in frontal view. B. Head and inner side of fore leg. C. Outer side of fore leg. D. Tegmina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413712/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). All dactyls pointed, the longest and most prominent being the mobile dactyls, with similar length; immobile dactyls of the tibia shorter than the articulated dactyls, the smallest being the ventral one (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBBFF95FDECFE03FD78FE7A" box="[630,718,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-28@4.[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in frontal view. B. Head and inner side of fore leg. C. Outer side of fore leg. D. Tegmina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413712/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Tarsal dactyl with rounded apex, the proximal or ventral dactyl is the longest, with the ventral margin uniformly curved; middle or dorsal dactyl as long as a quarter of the length of the ventral dactyl, with slightly wavy posterior edge; last tarsomere not modified, reduced, cylindrical and with two small distal claws (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBBFF95FE00FD97FE44FD96" box="[410,498,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-28@4.[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in frontal view. B. Head and inner side of fore leg. C. Outer side of fore leg. D. Tegmina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413712/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBBFF95FD9FFD96FDEEFD97" bold="true" box="[517,600,546,572]" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Wings.</emphasis>
Tegmina covering up to the second tergite, vein A2 not forked, anal 1 and 2 regions with numerous cross-veins, anal region 1 with three or four cross-veins; first cubital area with 2 or 3 crossveins (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBBFF95FF7AFDDFFE8CFD2E" box="[224,314,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-28@4.[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in frontal view. B. Head and inner side of fore leg. C. Outer side of fore leg. D. Tegmina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413712/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
). Hind wings surpass the length of the abdomen (
<figureCitation id="BF83D1CAFFBBFF95FCC2FDDFFC2EFD2E" box="[856,920,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,741,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-306@3.[151,1436,741,1883]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Gryllotalpella mendesi n. sp. Female A. Body in dorsal and B. Lateral view, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413710/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBBFF95FC35FDDEFB9DFD2F" bold="true" box="[943,1067,618,644]" pageId="3" pageNumber="486">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Edges of the dorsal groove of the last tergites with conspicuous setae, reddish and turning inwards. Epiproct triangular, wider than long. Subgenital plate wider than long and with a rounded edge.
</paragraph>
<caption id="73C79DC7FFBBFF95FF0DF8C6FB1FF820" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6413710" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6413710" box="[151,1193,1906,1931]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6413710/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="486" startId="3.[151,250,1906,1930]" targetBox="[151,1436,741,1883]" targetPageId="3">
