</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6FA29EC4FFBDFF93FF5DFEB6FBB9FE07" pageId="5" pageNumber="488" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2707CD4FFFBDFF93FF5DFEB6FBB9FE07" blockId="5.[151,1437,150,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="488">
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBDFF93FF5DFEB6FED4FEB7" bold="true" box="[199,354,258,284]" pageId="5" pageNumber="488">Comparison.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="E0B8B6CCFFBDFF93FEF2FEB7FE75FEB7" authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityYear="2015" box="[360,451,258,285]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllotalpidae" genus="Gryllotalpella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rehni">
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBDFF93FEF2FEB7FE75FEB7" box="[360,451,258,285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="488">G. rehni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the closest known species to the new species. The new species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="E0B8B6CCFFBDFF93FA85FEB7FACCFEB7" authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityYear="2015" box="[1311,1402,258,285]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllotalpidae" genus="Gryllotalpella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rehni">
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBDFF93FA85FEB7FACCFEB7" box="[1311,1402,258,285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="488">G. rehni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by a more elongated pronotum, ovoid ocelli, pointed dactyls, and tegminal venation. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName id="E0B8B6CCFFBDFF93FB2CFE93FAA5FEEB" authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityYear="2015" box="[1206,1299,294,321]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllotalpidae" genus="Gryllotalpella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rehni">
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBDFF93FB2CFE93FAA5FEEB" box="[1206,1299,294,321]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="488">G. rehni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has circular ocelli; moderately elongate pronotum; dactyls with the apex not sharp, and tympanum occupies 90% of the tibia base. Anal region 1 with five or six cross-veins; first cubital area with four cross-veins 
<emphasis id="15CC115DFFBDFF93FBF1FEDBFB3FFE23" box="[1131,1161,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="488">vs.</emphasis>
anal region 1 with three or four cross-veins; first cubital area with 2 or 3 cross-veins to the new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
